dismissalText.commentary: Dinesh Chandimal lbw b Shahid Afridi 28 (31b 1x4 2x6 36m) SR: 90.32

dismissalComment.html: Boom Boom strikes! Fires in a quick one and Chandimal is caught by surprise, bang straight on middle and he is beaten by the pace, struck in front of middle and the only issue may have been height but he hasn't asked for a referral, he goes after a briefly entertaining knock. Would have hit off and middle, and the height was okay

batsmen.shot: off side drive on front foot

commentTextItems.html: all over, sliding it on middle and leg, turned away through square leg into the deep, Pakistan have won this easily

commentPostTextItems.html: A cakewalk for the 'home' team, their spinners set it up by bowling Sri Lanka out for 131 and Farhat and Younis ensured there were no hiccups in the chase. Sri Lanka will be disappointed but they have a chance to make amends. Nitin Sundar's report is getting updated as I type. Join us in a bit for the presentation.

Shahid Afridi is Man of the Match for his three-for. An excellent comeback. Afridi: "Alhamdullilah, feeling great to come back in the international arena after a while. We have a good team combination at the moment, we're going through a rebuilding process. Misbah is leading the team very well."

Tillakaratne Dilshan: "We didn't start well. I didn't expect this performance. We didn't bat well, that's the main reason we lost. They bowled well in the first few overs, our shot selection wasn't very good. We have to come back strongly. We thank our fans for supporting us, we'll come back strongly."

Misbah-ul-Haq: "It's all about the team-work. The guys are doing a wonderful job. The fast bowlers gave us a good start, Hafeez and Afridi were brilliant. The bowlers are doing their job and putting them under pressure and getting wickets at the right time. The strength was our spinners, we stuck to the basics and they bowled well with the new ball. Afridi is a match-winner, he came on and bowled with a big heart. He took wickets at the right time and put us on the right track."
That's it for today. Thanks for tuning in and sending us your feedback. Join us for the next game, until then it's goodbye.

commentTextItems.html: banged in short, pulled away through square leg to Malinga in the deep for a single
back of a length outside off, stands tall to that one and defends it to point
thick outside edge, short of a good length, Younis opened the face on that one but it went much finer than he intended, went through the slips and gully for a boundary, just two needed now
shortish on the off, whips it past midwicket for an easy single
short of a good length outside off, gets an inside edge onto his pads as he tries to dab it into the off side

commentPreTextItems.html: Mark Kidger: "Like many English fans, I have a soft spot for both Pakistan and the West Indies. Pakistan because of their history of wonderful players (when you grow up watching players like Mushtaq, Sadiq, Zaheer Abbas, Imram Khan and Abdul Qadir you can't help it) and the West Indies who always seemed to pummel us from the mid-70s on, but they were just such magnificent players that you could only look on in wonder."

commentTextItems.html: short of a good length on the off, rocks back and knocks it into the off side

commentPreTextItems.html: A fine half-century from Farhat, Pakistan are almost there.

Shahrukh: "It really does feel that way, I think it's because Pakistan has gone through hell, and  really hit rock bottom last year. Maybe we are finally ready to become a serious force in world cricket, no more the mercurial, "very talented bunch of guys", but a dominating cricket force!! Too far??"
Sarfraz Ahmed, the wicketkeeper, is the new man in

dismissalText.commentary: Tillakaratne Dilshan b Aizaz Cheema 4 (8b 1x4 0x6 9m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: dragged it on! Short of a good length and it came back in, Dilshan prepared himself for a cut and the shot was on, but the nip back probably did him in as he inside-edged it back onto the stumps, one down

dismissalText.long: c Sarfaraz Ahmed b Abdul Razzaq
dismissalText.commentary: Kumar Sangakkara c Sarfaraz Ahmed b Abdul Razzaq 5 (24b 1x4 0x6 44m) SR: 20.83

dismissalComment.html: got him, a wicket in his first over, short of a good length outside off that held its line, Sanga tried to pinch a single by opening the face there, got a faint tickle and the keeper took a good, low catch. Sanga walked

dismissalText.long: c Aizaz Cheema b Mohammad Hafeez
dismissalText.commentary: Upul Tharanga c Aizaz Cheema b Mohammad Hafeez 25 (56b 2x4 0x6 85m) SR: 44.64

dismissalComment.html: Tharanga's efforts at improvisation fail him eventually, tossed up and he was looking to clear mid-on this time, tossed up and he struck it loosely straight to the fielder positioned there. Cheema took a straightforward catch

dismissalText.commentary: Dinesh Chandimal lbw b Shahid Afridi 28 (31b 1x4 2x6 36m) SR: 90.32

dismissalComment.html: Boom Boom strikes! Fires in a quick one and Chandimal is caught by surprise, bang straight on middle and he is beaten by the pace, struck in front of middle and the only issue may have been height but he hasn't asked for a referral, he goes after a briefly entertaining knock. Would have hit off and middle, and the height was okay

dismissalText.commentary: Angelo Mathews run out (Abdul Razzaq/Sarfaraz Ahmed) 10 (31b 0x4 0x6 31m) SR: 32.25

dismissalComment.html: a run-out ends Mathews' stay, that was tucked behind square leg, there was no run in it, though Mathews seemed to think there was, he charges down the track before being turned back, he dives to try make his ground, but the throw was at the top of the stumps and the keeper whips off the bails before Mathews can return

dismissalComment.html: not the best of debuts with the bat for Kulasekara, was clearly sucked in by the flight there, tempting delivery that landed full on the off and he chipped it loosely straight towards a perfectly-positioned mid-off, a dolly of a catch to Umar Gul
